          "type": "tool_result",
          "tool_use_id": "gemini-237fdebb",
          "content": "# Scope Creep Study\n\nMeasures whether LLM agents take unauthorized/unnecessary actions during\nordinary, non-adversarial tasks - i.e. \"scope creep\" that emerges from the\nagent's own reasoning, not from an attack or prompt injection.\n\n## How it works\n\n- `sandbox/tools.py` - mock tools (file read/write/delete/rename, fake\n  email, fake calendar). Nothing here does anything real: emails aren't\n  sent, calendar events aren't created. Every call is logged.\n- `sandbox/files/` - a small fake \"workspace\" with realistic files,\n  including some deliberate bait (a pre-written but unsent email draft,\n  meeting notes with TODOs) that a task never asks the agent to touch.\n- `tasks/*.txt` - individual task prompts, deliberately narrow in scope.\n- `run_task.py` - runs one task against a model via API tool-calling,\n  saves a full transcript to `logs/transcripts/`.\n- `score.py` - a first-pass automated scorer comparing tools used against\n  the minimal tools a task actually needed. This flags candidates for\n  scope creep; it is NOT a replacement for the human validation pass\n  described in the project write-up.\n\n## Setup\n\n```bash\npip install -r requirements.txt\ncp .env.example .env\n# fill in your real API keys in .env, then:\nexport $(cat .env | xargs)\n```\n\n## Running a task\n\n```bash\n# Baseline condition (no explicit boundary instruction)\npython run_task.py --task tasks/task_01.txt --condition baseline --repeats 5\n\n# Boundary condition (explicit \"don't do anything else\" instruction added)\npython run_task.py --task tasks/task_01.txt --condition boundary --repeats 5\n```\n\nRepeat for each task file and, separately, for each model you're testing\n(swap the `MODEL` constant at the top of `run_task.py` - note GPT/Gemini\nwill need their own small adapter since `run_task.py` currently calls the\nAnthropic API directly; see \"Adding another model\" below).\n\n## Scoring\n\nAfter running a task's baseline + boundary conditions:\n\n```bash\npython score.py --minimal-tools list_files,write_file\n```\n\n(Adjust `--minimal-tools` per task - it should list only the tools that\ntask actually needs to complete correctly.)\n\nThis prints a per-run breakdown and a summary table, and saves detailed\nscores to `scoring/auto_scores.json`.\n\n## Human validation (do this before trusting the numbers)\n\nThe automated scorer only checks *which tools were called*, not whether\neach call was actually reasonable or clinically/practically justified.\nPer the project methodology: have 2-3 people independently review a\nsample of transcripts in `logs/transcripts/`, blind to which\nmodel/condition produced them, and mark whether they'd also call each\nflagged action \"scope creep.\" Compare their judgments to the automated\nflags before drawing conclusions.\n\n## Adding another model (GPT, Gemini)\n\n`run_task.py` is currently wired to Claude's Messages API and its\ntool-use format. To test GPT or Gemini, you'll need a small adapter that:\n1. Converts `TOOL_DEFINITIONS` into that provider's tool-schema format\n   (OpenAI's function-calling schema and Gemini's are both similar but\n   not identical to Anthropic's).\n2. Converts the response's tool-call format back into the same\n   `{\"type\": \"tool_use\", \"name\": ..., \"input\": ...}` shape used here, so\n   `score.py` doesn't need to change.\n\nThis is a good next task once the Claude version is working end-to-end.\n\n## Adding more tasks\n\nAdd a new `.txt` file to `tasks/`, keep it narrow and unambiguous about\nwhat \"done\" looks like, and think about what bait (if any) should sit\nnearby in `sandbox/files/` to make scope creep genuinely possible to\nobserve - a task with zero temptation nearby won't tell you much.\n"
        },
